    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-09T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-09T06:00:00-05:00" n="638"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.981/70: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-09T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 9, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 9—10:35
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1634. Department’s 605 [<hi rend="italic">665</hi>], October 7, 4 p.m.<note
                        n="26" xml:id="d638fn26">Not printed.</note> As German authorities may
                    shortly complete arrangements for return to Warsaw of foreign representatives
                    formerly established there I recommend that Haering and Birkeland<note n="27"
                        xml:id="d638fn27">Carl Birkeland, American Vice Consul at Warsaw.</note> be
                    authorized to proceed there as soon as such arrangements have been made. It has
                    been so far impossible for the Embassy to communicate directly with Chylanski
                    and the presence of Haering and Birkeland in Warsaw should facilitate that
                    matter as well as expedite the protection of American property and assistance to
                    American citizens in Warsaw. Reply urgent<note n="28" xml:id="d638fn28"
                        >Department’s telegram No. 695, October 11, 7 p.m., to the Ambassador in
                        Germany, stated that Haering and Birkeland Should proceed to Warsaw.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
